  "title": "Types of redox reactions",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Redox reaction",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>&nbsp;Oxidation - Reaction</strong></h3><p><strong>Oxidation </strong>is a process that involves the loss of electrons by the atoms or ions. <strong>Reduction </strong>is a process that involves the gain of electrons by atoms or ions. Any reaction in which the electrons are exchanged between atoms or ions, represents simultaneous process of oxidation and reduction is called as <strong>Redox Reaction </strong>.</p><p>In a Redox Reaction, the species that loses electron (i.e., gets oxidised) is known as <strong>reducing agent </strong>or <strong>reductant </strong>, (since it causes reduction of other species), the species which accepts electrons from other reductant (i.e., gets reduced) is known as <strong>oxidising agent </strong>or <strong>oxidant </strong>(as it causes oxidation of other species).</p><p>To illustrate:</p><p>$\\text{Mg}+\\text{Z}{{\\text{n}}^{2+}}\\text{M}{{\\text{g}}^{2+}}+\\text{Zn}$ is a redox reaction.</p><p>Oxidation: $\\text{M}{{\\text{g}}^{0}}-2\\text{e}-\\to \\text{M}{{\\text{g}}^{2+}}$</p><p>Reduction: $\\text{Z}{{\\text{n}}^{2+}}+2\\text{e}-\\to \\text{Z}{{\\text{n}}^{0}}$</p><p>$\\text{Mg}$ causes reduction of $\\text{Z}{{\\text{n}}^{2+}}$, so it is Reductant.</p><p>$\\text{Z}{{\\text{n}}^{2+}}$ causes oxidation of $\\text{Mg}$, so it is oxidant.</p><p>Note: A redox reaction involves two half reactions:</p><p>Oxidation and Reduction half reactions.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcd5c03b9dcaf1afe7eb"
    },
    {
      "title": "Oxidation half Reactions",
      "conceptBody": "<p><strong>(1) Molecular Reaction:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>When one molecule gets oxidised and other gets reduced in a chemical reaction.</p><p>e.g.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>Here $\\text{Mn}{{\\text{O}}_{2}}$ is getting oxidised and in $\\text{KMn}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}$ is getting reduced (In two different molecules). So it is intramolecular reaction.</p><p><strong>(2) Intramolecular Reaction:</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong>When oxidation and reduction takes place in the same molecule.</p><p>e.g. $\\overset{-3}{\\mathop{\\text{N}{{\\text{H}}_{4}}}}\\,\\overset{+5}{\\mathop{\\text{N}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}}}\\,\\xrightarrow{{}}{{\\overset{+1}{\\mathop{~\\text{N}}}\\,}_{2}}\\text{O}+2{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$</p><p>In this example one $\\text{N}$ is getting reduced and other is getting oxidised in the same molecule $\\text{N}{{\\text{H}}_{4}}\\text{N}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}$. So it is a intramolecular reaction.</p><p><strong>(3) Disproportionation Reaction:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>When same element gets oxidised and reduced in a reaction.</p><p>e.g. $4{{\\text{H}}_{3}}{{\\overset{+3}{\\mathop{\\text{PO}}}\\,}_{3}}\\xrightarrow{{}}3{{\\text{H}}_{3}}\\overset{+5}{\\mathop{\\text{P}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}}}\\,+\\overset{-3}{\\mathop{\\text{P}{{\\text{H}}_{3}}}}\\,$</p><p>Here only one P is oxidised as well as reduced. So it is disproportionation reaction.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcd6c03b9dcaf1afe7ec"
    }
  ],
